    "subtlety_eigenvalue_coincidence": "A remarkable feature of S^3 is that the scalar Laplacian eigenvalues (n^2-1 at level n in Fock convention) numerically EQUAL the Hodge-1 eigenvalues (n(n+2) at level n) after a level shift: scalar(n+1) = (n+1)^2-1 = n^2+2n = n(n+2) = Hodge-1(n). This means L_1 (which has the scalar spectrum by SVD) already has eigenvalues that are VALUES in the Hodge-1 spectrum. The difference is purely in the SECTOR ASSIGNMENT: L_1 puts these eigenvalues in the exact sector, while the physical photon needs them in the co-exact sector. On S^3 with Hodge duality, both sectors have eigenvalue n(n+2) -- so the VALUES are right, the PHYSICS is wrong (longitudinal, not transverse)."
